PRIVATE STRATEGIC REFLECTION – ROUND 1/6  

1. PROPOSAL ANALYSIS  
• Most successful: MY opening package {o3: 1,3 | h1: 0,2 | h2: 4}. It satisfied both partners’ minimum requirements while maximizing my own payoff (I kept the pair 1,3 that I value highest).  
• Why it worked:  
  – haiku_agent_2 received item 4 (they never proposed any deal without 4, so 4 appears to be their must-have).  
  – haiku_agent_1 received two items. Although they initially asked for {1,3}, they seem to care more about quantity or about having a “pair” than the specific identities; 0 + 2 was an acceptable substitute.  
• Least successful: The two counter-proposals gave h1 the lucrative pair (1,3) and left me with weaker bundles; I vetoed them. Without my vote they could get only 1/3 support.  
• Strategic positioning: By moving first and explicitly granting each haiku agent something core to its revealed wish list (h2’s 4, h1’s two-item bundle), I framed my offer as the focal point. The others then had to justify taking value away from someone who already accepted a “fair” split.

2. VOTING PATTERNS  
• Each proposer always voted for their own deal (unsurprising).  
• Both haiku agents were ultimately willing to vote for my offer, showing they are pragmatic rather than purely item-fixated.  
• Alignment clues:  
  – h1 & h2 seem loosely coordinated: their two proposals share the structure “h1 gets 1,3; h2 gets 4.”  
  – However, h2 did not hold out for that structure once 4 was secured, so their alliance is soft.  
• No evidence of strategic “poison-pill” voting yet; everyone simply rejected bundles that hurt them.

3. COMMUNICATION INSIGHTS  
• Preference signals extracted:  
  – haiku_agent_2: Item 4 is critical; they never relinquished it.  
  – haiku_agent_1: Wants two items, and 1+3 is the ideal pair but 0+2 is good enough.  
• Transparency: h2 was consistent and therefore predictable; h1 revealed flexibility once they faced the prospect of stalemate.  
• No obvious deception, threats or anchoring language—early round congeniality.

4. STRATEGIC LEARNINGS  
What worked:  
  ✓ First-mover advantage—anchored discourse around my preferred bundle.  
  ✓ Gave each counterpart at least one “headline” concession (4 for h2, two items for h1).  
Improvements:  
  – Elicit clearer numeric preferences; right now my picture is qualitative. I should ask gentle preference-probing questions next time to refine utility estimates.  
  – Prepare fall-back offer that still keeps 1 or 3 if opponents hard-demand both.  
Forward strategy:  
  • Continue granting h2 item 4 in most offers to lock in their support.  
  • Offer h1 two-item bundles, experimenting which pairs they rank second-best (0+2 worked; maybe 0+1, 2+3?).  
  • Propose quickly each round before the haiku agents coordinate on an alternative favorable to them.

5. RELATIONSHIP DYNAMICS  
• Coalition potential: Strong with haiku_agent_2 (shared interest = give them 4, get their vote).  
• Negotiation difficulty: Moderate with haiku_agent_1—they have the most variable wants but are still persuadable if they receive two pieces.  
• Exploitation risk: Limited so far. No agent tried to push an obviously one-sided deal after seeing my acceptance threshold.  

Actionable memory to carry forward  
– haiku_agent_2 treats item 4 as indispensable.  
– haiku_agent_1 cares primarily about receiving two items; item identity secondary (ideal pair 1+3, acceptable 0+2).  
– Early anchoring plus targeted concessions secures consensus and protects my high-value items (1,3).
